vars: {
  d2-config: {
    layout-engine: elk
    theme-id: 6
  }
}
title: |md
  ## seq_file Mechanics: Why `proc_read` Breaks vs. Why `seq_file` Works
  *Milestone 3 — /proc/mydevice via seq_file*
| {near: top-center}
# ─── LEFT SIDE: BROKEN NAIVE APPROACH ───────────────────────────────────────
broken: "❌  NAIVE: proc_read Callback" {
  style: {
    fill: "#3d1a1a"
    stroke: "#cc3333"
    stroke-width: 3
    border-radius: 8
  }
  step_b1: "Step 1 — Kernel Invokes Callback" {
    style: { fill: "#5a2020"; stroke: "#cc3333"; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      **`proc_read(buf, start, offset, count, eof, data)`**
      - `buf` = fixed kernel-supplied char buffer
      - **Hard limit: 4096 bytes (1 page)**
      - `offset` = byte position to resume from
      - `count` = userspace read() request size
    |
  }
  step_b2: "Step 2 — Driver Generates Output" {
    style: { fill: "#5a2020"; stroke: "#cc3333"; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      c
      /* DANGEROUS — naive pattern */
      int len = sprintf(buf,
        "buffer_size: %zu\n"
        "bytes_used:  %zu\n"
        /* ... more fields ... */
        "field_50: %s\n",   /* 50 fields */
        ...);
      *eof = 1;
      return len;
      
    |
  }
  step_b3: "Step 3 — Silent Truncation Bug" {
    style: { fill: "#7a1515"; stroke: "#ff4444"; stroke-width: 2; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      **⚠ OUTPUT > 4096 BYTES?**
      `sprintf` overwrites beyond `buf` end
      → **buffer overflow in kernel memory**
      → OR `snprintf` silently truncates at 4096
      → userspace `cat` sees incomplete data
      → **no error returned — silent failure**
    |
  }
  step_b4: "Step 4 — Broken Partial-Read Offset Logic" {
    style: { fill: "#7a1515"; stroke: "#ff4444"; stroke-width: 2; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      **When userspace calls `read(fd, buf, 512)` multiple times:**
      `offset` parameter must track position.
      Driver must manually slice output string.
      Historical bugs (thousands of drivers):
      - Off-by-one in offset calculation
      - Infinite loop: `read()` never returns 0
      - Data duplication across chunk boundaries
      - `cat` hangs or produces garbled output
    |
  }
  bug_box: "🐛  Root Cause" {
    style: { fill: "#4a0000"; stroke: "#ff2222"; stroke-width: 3; border-radius: 8 }
    label: |md
      **Fixed-size buffer + manual offset tracking**
      is fundamentally incompatible with
      arbitrary-length kernel output delivered
      in arbitrary-sized userspace `read()` chunks.
      **This API was deprecated. Do not use it.**
    |
  }
  step_b1 -> step_b2: "kernel calls back"
  step_b2 -> step_b3: "output > 4096?"
  step_b3 -> step_b4: "multi-chunk reads"
  step_b4 -> bug_box: "systemic failure"
}
# ─── RIGHT SIDE: CORRECT SEQ_FILE APPROACH ───────────────────────────────────
correct: "✅  CORRECT: seq_file with single_open" {
  style: {
    fill: "#0d2e1a"
    stroke: "#33cc66"
    stroke-width: 3
    border-radius: 8
  }
  # ── single_open internals ──
  single_open_box: "single_open() — Setup Phase" {
    style: { fill: "#1a4a2a"; stroke: "#33cc66"; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      **`single_open(filp, mydevice_proc_show, NULL)`**
      Allocates `struct seq_file` on the heap.
      Stores in `filp->private_data`.
      c
      struct seq_file {
        char          *buf;      /* dynamic page list  */
        size_t         size;     /* current buf size   */
        size_t         from;     /* offset within buf  */
        size_t         count;    /* bytes in buf       */
        loff_t         index;    /* iterator position  */
        void          *private;  /* = NULL (our data)  */
        struct seq_operations *op;  /* start/next/stop/show */
      };
      
      Sets `op->show = mydevice_proc_show`.
    |
  }
  # ── seq_read handles fragmentation ──
  seq_read_box: "seq_read() — Fragment Manager (provided by kernel)" {
    style: { fill: "#1a4a2a"; stroke: "#33cc66"; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      **Called by VFS on every `read(fd, buf, N)` userspace call.**
      Internal logic:
      
      if internal_buffer is empty:
          call show(seq_file, v)   ← fills internal buf
      copy min(N, count) bytes → userspace
      advance seq_file.from by bytes copied
      if all bytes delivered:
          set EOF flag
      return bytes copied (or 0 for EOF)
      
      Handles **any N** transparently.
      No driver code needed for fragmentation.
    |
  }
  # ── show function ──
  show_box: "mydevice_proc_show() — Your Code" {
    style: { fill: "#1a4a2a"; stroke: "#33cc66"; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      c
      static int mydevice_proc_show(
              struct seq_file *m, void *v)
      {
          seq_printf(m, "buffer_size:  %zu\n",
                     buffer_size);
          seq_printf(m, "bytes_used:   %zu\n",
                     buffer_data_len);
          seq_printf(m, "open_count:   %d\n",
                     atomic_read(&open_count));
          seq_printf(m, "read_count:   %d\n",
                     atomic_read(&read_count));
          seq_printf(m, "write_count:  %d\n",
                     atomic_read(&write_count));
          return 0;  /* always */
      }
      
      **Never check `seq_printf` return value.**
      Buffer overflow is handled internally
      by allocating additional pages.
    |
  }
  # ── seq_printf internals ──
  seq_printf_box: "seq_printf() — Dynamic Buffer Growth" {
    style: { fill: "#0f3320"; stroke: "#22aa44"; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      **On each `seq_printf(m, fmt, ...)`:**
      1. `vsnprintf` into `m->buf + m->count`
      2. If remaining space < needed bytes:
         → `seq_buf_alloc()` doubles buffer size
         → copies existing content to new allocation
         → retries the printf
      3. `m->count += bytes_written`
      **Result: buffer grows to fit any output.**
      No driver-visible size limit.
      No driver-visible truncation.
    |
  }
  # ── delivery sequence ──
  delivery_box: "Delivery to Userspace — Any Chunk Size" {
    style: { fill: "#0f3320"; stroke: "#22aa44"; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      **`cat /proc/mydevice`** calls read() with 4096-byte buf:
      → `seq_read` calls `show()` once → ~80 bytes generated
      → copies 80 bytes → userspace
      → next read() returns 0 → cat exits ✓
      **`dd if=/proc/mydevice bs=1`** calls read() 1 byte at a time:
      → `seq_read` calls `show()` once → 80 bytes in internal buf
      → delivers 1 byte per call, tracking `from` offset
      → after 80 calls, returns 0 → dd exits ✓
      **No driver code changes needed between these cases.**
    |
  }
  proc_ops_box: "proc_ops Registration" {
    style: { fill: "#1a4a2a"; stroke: "#33cc66"; border-radius: 6 }
    label: |md
      c
      static const struct proc_ops mydevice_proc_ops = {
          .proc_open    = mydevice_proc_open,
          /* provided by seq_file infrastructure: */
          .proc_read    = seq_read,
          .proc_lseek   = seq_lseek,
          .proc_release = single_release,
      };
      proc_create("mydevice", 0444, NULL,
                  &mydevice_proc_ops);
      
      **Only `proc_open` and `show()` are yours.**
      Everything else: kernel provides.
    |
  }
  single_open_box -> show_box: "registers show callback"
  show_box -> seq_printf_box: "seq_printf() calls"
  seq_printf_box -> seq_read_box: "fills internal buffer"
  seq_read_box -> delivery_box: "delivers any chunk size"
  proc_ops_box -> single_open_box: "open() triggers"
}
# ─── COMPARISON CONNECTORS ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
vs_label: "VS" {
  shape: circle
  style: {
    fill: "#444444"
    stroke: "#888888"
    font-size: 22
    bold: true
    font-color: "#ffffff"
  }
}
broken -> vs_label: "" {
  style: { stroke: "#cc3333"; stroke-dash: 3; stroke-width: 2 }
}
vs_label -> correct: "" {
  style: { stroke: "#33cc66"; stroke-width: 2 }
}
# ─── BOTTOM SUMMARY ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
summary: |md
  **Key Rule:** Call `proc_create("mydevice", 0444, NULL, &mydevice_proc_ops)` in `mydevice_init`.
  Call `proc_remove(proc_entry)` **first** in `mydevice_exit` — before `kfree(kernel_buffer)` — because a concurrent `cat` reader
  may still be inside `mydevice_proc_show` accessing `buffer_data_len`. `proc_remove` blocks until all readers finish.
  On kernel ≥ 5.6: use `struct proc_ops`. On kernel < 5.6: use `struct file_operations` for `/proc` entries.
| {
  near: bottom-center
  style: {
    fill: "#1a1a2e"
    stroke: "#555599"
    stroke-width: 2
    border-radius: 8
    font-size: 13
  }
}